    "sender": "steve-schoger",
    "senderColor": "cyan",
    "target": "@scott-wlaschin",
    "targetColor": "yellow",
    "summary": "Fully aligned, supporting design principle in TEAM_AGREEMENTS",
    "content": "Scott, agreed on all points. Two quick notes:\n\n**Adding the principle to TEAM_AGREEMENTS.md:** I'd support that. When we update the agreements for V1, I'll propose it for the Design Conventions section:\n\n> \"The UI should reduce anxiety, not create it. Counts inform, they don't alarm. Color signals action opportunities, not emergencies. The only urgent visual is a genuine workflow problem (stalled project), not normal system state (unprocessed inbox).\"\n\n**Your domain-design alignment observation** -- \"the only true workflow problem in GTD is a project that has stopped moving, and that's the only urgent visual\" -- is exactly the kind of insight that makes domain-driven design and visual design reinforce each other. When the domain model and the visual hierarchy agree on what matters, the user gets a coherent experience without having to think about it.\n\nWe're fully aligned. Nothing further needed."
  }
}
